- Fri 30 Aug 2019. Misinformaiton
[Telegraph (abridged, edited)]
https://www.telegraph.co.uk/global-health/science-and-disease/misinformation-driving-drcs-ebola-outbreak/

[Byline: Thuong Nguyen]

Misinformation is driving DRC's Ebola outbreak - but the community is the key to beating it

Ebola in Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) has reached another tragic milestone this week, with more than 2000 deaths recorded. While there has been more heartening news recently thanks to a trial of new Ebola treatments, the outbreak is far from under control and is still the worst the country has ever seen.

I was in the Democratic Republic of Congo at the start of the Ebola outbreak. I'm not a doctor. My job was to collate and analyse data. It's not something that sounds obvious for an Ebola operation, but the Red Cross needed a way to measure and understand the progress of the operation and what was hampering it.

It was clear from an early stage that this outbreak would be challenging. Some communities didn't want us to change the traditional way they buried people despite the risks associated with handling the dead. There were various rumours and ideas about Ebola and how it was spread. Some people didn't believe the virus was real.

With the local volunteers, we set up a system to map rumours and feedback. So far, the Red Cross has collected over 33 000 pieces of community feedback. These range from questions about how Ebola is passed on, to theories about treatment, to outright denial the virus exists. By looking at the beliefs and feedback, volunteers can adjust the response. For example, a transparent body bag was developed to help counter rumours that the bags contained rubble instead of people. It's amazing to see how data collection can have a real impact in an emergency.

It was challenging carrying out such a tech-heavy role in this environment. We had to ship in extra IT kit from nearby cities and other countries. The internet was quite difficult at times. That was frustrating when you're trying to do mobile data gathering in real time. We had to build up the infrastructure from scratch.

Just over a year on, many of the challenges remain. There is no quick fix. Many people continue to believe the outbreak is fake. If you think about it, this isn't that surprising. If people turned up at your door in weird suits and told you there was a deadly virus, it would be strange in any country. But this region is complex. It's not like you can just check things with a reliable source of information. There is little technology in rural areas. You hear something from your neighbour and you believe it.

The Red Cross' safe and dignified burial teams play a hugely important role in this response. People continue to be infectious for as long as 7 days after death from Ebola. Victims need to be buried immediately and by people who are appropriately dressed and trained.

Yet doing so can inevitably interfere with traditional burial rituals at what is a very sensitive time for families and communities. Most times, our teams are accepted and can work with families so the burial goes ahead safely. Other times, they're refused access. In the worst cases, the refusal becomes violent. These volunteers, who carry out the riskiest work, have so far escaped infection from Ebola, but have been hospitalised due to attacks.

In the face of these extraordinarily difficult circumstances, we owe a huge debt of gratitude to the community-based volunteers on the front lines of this response. All the volunteers I met were very enthusiastic and dedicated. They came to work despite difficult circumstances. Sometimes there were shootings or attacks -- even in front of their homes -- and they'd still want to come into work.

These volunteers and the people of the DRC have suffered long enough. As this crisis passes yet another terrible landmark, we need to continue listening to what the community is thinking and feeling if we are going to succeed in eradicating this disease.

--
